<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="micro-mvps">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-planning</domain>
    <summary>Extremely small, high-signal experiments to validate one key assumption in hours to days using six experiment types: landing page, concierge, Wizard of Oz, video demo, fake door, smoke test.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>mvp</tag>
      <tag>validation</tag>
      <tag>experiments</tag>
      <tag>lean</tag>
      <tag>rapid-testing</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Micro-MVPs</title>
    <summary>Micro-MVPs are extremely small, high-signal experiments designed to validate one key assumption in hours to days rather than weeks. Six experiment types (landing page, concierge, Wizard of Oz, video demo, fake door, smoke test) map to specific assumption categories. The pattern forces assumption identification, success-metric definition, and a pivot/persevere decision before starting, not after.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Traditional MVPs still take weeks or months to build, yet most failed products fail on assumptions that could be tested in a day. Micro-MVPs compress the validate-or-kill cycle by orders of magnitude: Dropbox validated file-sync demand with a 3-minute video before writing a line of sync code. The pattern is: identify the riskiest assumption, design the smallest experiment, define success in advance.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>New product idea where demand, willingness-to-pay, or workflow fit is unvalidated.</item>
        <item>Feature hypothesis that can be faked before building (Wizard of Oz, fake door).</item>
        <item>Budget or time is too constrained for a full MVP build.</item>
        <item>Iterating rapidly post-MVP to validate the next bet without a full sprint.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Assumption already validated by strong existing evidence — skip to build.</item>
        <item>Regulated domains where a "fake" product violates compliance (fintech, medical).</item>
        <item>Infrastructure/platform work with no user-facing surface to fake.</item>
        <item>When the experiment would damage brand trust with early adopters.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="experiment-types">
      <p>Six micro-MVP experiment types mapped to effort range and what each one validates.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Match the experiment type to the assumption category. Do not build a landing page to validate willingness-to-pay; use a smoke test instead.</statement>
        <rationale>Each experiment type has a different signal type. Using the wrong type wastes time and produces misleading data.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Landing page (1 day): validates demand and messaging. Shows a description of the product and measures sign-up rate or email capture.</item>
        <item>Concierge (1 week): validates workflow and core value. Manually deliver the product's promise to 5–10 users to discover the real job-to-be-done.</item>
        <item>Wizard of Oz (days): validates UX and willingness-to-pay. Fake automated product backed by manual human fulfilment; users interact as if it is real.</item>
        <item>Video demo (hours): validates interest and virality. Record the product promise; measure views, shares, and comments before building anything.</item>
        <item>Fake door (hours): validates feature demand. Add a button or menu item for a feature that does not exist yet; measure click rate before building.</item>
        <item>Smoke test (days): validates price sensitivity and conversion. Offer the product for purchase; measure conversion at the target price point before delivering.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="dropbox-example">
      <example type="good">
        <note>Assumption: people want easy file sync across devices.</note>
        <note>Micro-MVP: a 3-minute video explaining the concept, posted online. No code written.</note>
        <note>Result: waitlist jumped from 5,000 to 75,000 overnight. Validated demand without building a single byte of sync infrastructure.</note>
        <note>Cost: video production time only.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="micro-mvp-process">
      <p>Six-step process for designing, running, and acting on a micro-MVP experiment.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 1: Identify the riskiest assumption — the one belief, if wrong, that kills the product idea entirely.</statement>
        <rationale>Testing a secondary assumption first wastes time. Riskiest assumption first forces prioritisation by existential risk, not build convenience.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 2: Design the smallest experiment that can falsify or confirm that single assumption. One assumption per experiment.</statement>
        <rationale>Multi-assumption experiments produce ambiguous results. If the experiment fails, you do not know which assumption was wrong.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 3: Define success metrics before starting, not after seeing results. Specify the threshold that means "confirmed" vs "rejected".</statement>
        <rationale>Defining metrics after seeing results produces motivated reasoning. Pre-commitment makes the experiment falsifiable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 4: Run the experiment in hours to days. If it takes longer than one week, it is not a micro-MVP — split or simplify.</statement>
        <rationale>Speed is the whole point. A week-long micro-MVP competes with a two-week sprint and loses the argument for the lighter method.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 5: Analyse results against the pre-defined threshold. Binary outcome: confirmed or rejected.</statement>
        <rationale>Avoiding a clear verdict extends limbo. Even a failed experiment is valuable — it redirects effort before a full build.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Step 6: Decide: pivot (change the assumption and test again), persevere (move to building), or test the next riskiest assumption.</statement>
        <rationale>One confirmed micro-MVP is not enough to build. Stack experiments until the top 2–3 existential assumptions are validated before committing to a sprint.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Running a micro-MVP for an assumption already validated by strong existing evidence.</description>
        <reason>Over-testing wastes time. Reserve micro-MVPs for genuinely uncertain assumptions; skip experiments where evidence already converges.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Skipping the pre-defined success threshold and interpreting results after the fact.</description>
        <reason>Post-hoc interpretation always finds a way to confirm the hypothesis. Pre-commitment is what makes the experiment honest.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.dropbox.com/blog/dropbox-story"/>
